(90, 1, '2023-11-06 01:39:38', '2023-11-06 01:39:38', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The&nbsp;<code>include</code>&nbsp;(or&nbsp;<code>require</code>) statement takes all the text/code/markup that exists in the specified file and copies it into the file that uses the include statement.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Including files is very useful when you want to include the same PHP, HTML, or text on multiple pages of a website.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">PHP include and require Statements</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It is possible to insert the content of one PHP file into another PHP file (before the server executes it), with the include or require statement.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>The include and require statements are identical, except upon failure:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code>require</code>&nbsp;will produce a fatal error (E_COMPILE_ERROR) and stop the script</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code>include</code>&nbsp;will only produce a warning (E_WARNING) and the script will continue</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So, if you want the execution to go on and show users the output, even if the include file is missing, use the include statement. Otherwise, in case of FrameWork, CMS, or a complex PHP application coding, always use the require statement to include a key file to the flow of execution. This will help avoid compromising your application\'s security and integrity, just in-case one key file is accidentally missing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Including files saves a lot of work. This means that you can create a standard header, footer, or menu file for all your web pages. Then, when the header needs to be updated, you can only update the header include file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'PHP Advanced', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'php-advanced', '', '', '2023-11-06 01:39:38', '2023-11-06 01:39:38', '', 0, 'http://localhost:82/wordpress/?p=90', 0, 'post', '', 0);
